segments.text: They took on a lot of different subjects.
They were truthful and sincere about it.

They didn't follow journalistic rules, which tries to say there's such a thing as objectivity, which if you get out and analyze what's objective and what's subjective, you're going to run into major problems.
Everybody that writes something is making decisions about what's in there and what's not in there and what words are used.
and how you string those together, what questions you ask, what questions you don't ask.

So they let people write, you know, this is what I believe, this is what I see, and it had a big impact, not only on just the activist community and helped to build resistance, but it had an impact on the media at that time.
And that leads me to another thing that we did together, a bunch of them,
We held media conferences, had three of them in Texas, and I think this is reported in the Observer.
I'm not sure.
We had one in Austin, the first one.
We had one in Dallas, and we had one in Houston.
The basic, the original idea came from Alice Embree, the woman I was telling you about a minute ago.
She was one of the original people that worked on the RAG, helped put it together.
She's also one of the people who was active in National SDS, went to New York City early,
on she really knew a lot understands a lot still does very intense wonderful person and she had this idea that we could reach a lot of these people in the media these reporters don't like
for a goddamn editor or publisher to say, you can't do this, don't do this, write this, don't write that.
It makes horrors out of piss.
Who the hell have I?
I can't tell the truth.

And of course, there are the ones who still do that write a lot of the stories or feed a lot of the stories to the observer and other folks where they cannot have their name attached to it because they lose their job.

At any rate, Alice's idea was that we can reach a lot of these media people, and we'll get some better stories, and we'll get some more information from within, if we do reach them, and not in any manipulative way.
In other words, make all of this open.
What we're trying to do is open up a dialogue between reporters and TV people and radio people and the new left.
So we had these new left media comments.
I did the advance work on that again.

She knew a good many of the media people and I did too because I'd worked in Texas Liberal Democratic Party politics and I knew how to get around all the stations and newspapers and hand out press releases and bullshit and drink martinis and all that crap.
And we had a good conference.
We got a lot of young media people.
And
In Dallas, I don't know how many we had.
I guess we probably ended up with 30 or 40.
We had people there from the Dallas Morning News, the Dallas Times, Arrow, the major TV stations.
Of course, the underground media, I forgot the name of that one.
There was a good underground paper up there.
And these weren't folks just there to rat on us to their owners.
Well, there were some of those, but a lot of very sincere young people in the media.
And it worked well.

I mean, they found out, people always find out when they get out of their little isolation boxes that there are a lot of other people that are worried about the same things they're worried about and have some of the same problems.
And that it is possible to do a few things, and sometimes it's possible to do a whole lot, but you've got to do them together.
At any rate, all of that dynamic occurred because they told each other horror stories about, you know,
You know, when such and such story came out, well, here's what really happened.
This is why I couldn't do this.
And they said, well, listen to this.
And God damn, if the American people as a whole could have heard all of that stuff on TV, it would have been great.
The problem always is reaching folks so that they can get information.
We did that one in Dallas.
We did one in Houston.
We did one here.
A lot of those people, it changed their lives, too.
I know here locally, there were two women.
There were reporters on the American station, Austin American, who quit.
Not immediately thereafter, but in recent years, said that those media conferences had an impact on what they decided to do with their lives.
They decided they weren't gonna continue writing the same old shit and doing the same old thing.
Even though one of them is now
She's a poet and a writer.
Fiction.
Short story.
Okay.
Tonight, you know, we're talking about Rubin and Hoffman.
Two people who know a whole lot about the media.
And really changed a lot of things as far as
is the way the media looks at things now, because they manipulated the hell out of the media.
They pulled a lot of good theater.
I mean, they've dramatized things where then one TV station would have to carry it, because if they didn't, another one would.
And first thing you know, demonstrations and a whole lot of the different activities were getting coverage just because the nature of the competition between some of the capitalists
They had the same basic principles, but they felt like they had to carry this stuff.
So they opened themselves up to being manipulated.
And I guess you heard about the one where Abbie Hoffman went into the Wall Street exchange and threw dollar bills all over the floor of the stock exchange that day.
They had all those fucking clerks and guys scrambling around on the floor picking up dollar bills.
Which, if you think about it, there are these young clerk guys out of Harvard and Yale
trying to climb the squirrel cage, get up the ladder, and button boys for million-dollar purchases.
But there comes a dollar bill down on the floor, and there they are scrambling after.
At any rate, it showed some of the contradictions of what was going on.
The media, a lot of them were very sympathetic.
You know the chuck wagon case?
Long times past, I wouldn't even talk about this.
I mean, all the legal ramifications yet is, is, uh, is over.
Uh, that TV people there, they were there that day of the demonstration, got all kinds of footage and after the arrest and after the,
It became clear that the establishment here in Austin was going to try to make felony cases out of this, which is ridiculous.
They were trying to send people to prison for relatively minor free speech activities.
What they did was contact us individually and surreptitiously.
Thank you.
And there's two of them.
They made it possible.
I was in charge of collecting the evidence.
And we had to have good security on that because some evidence is helpful, some evidence is harmful.
And it's not the defense's responsibility on the so-called American system to make the case for the prosecution.
So I'm under no responsibility to help the state make a case.
The contrary is not true about the state, by the way.
They're supposed to open up and disclose what they have, which is what happened in this Hurricane Carter case.
You know about that?
This guy just got out of prison.
It's been 19 years.
Bob Dylan wrote the song about him.
Well, what happened in that case, the prosecution did not make a lot of information available that would have been helpful to the defense in that case.
Finally, 19 years later, a fucking judge says, no, that ain't part of our constitution.
Let the guy out.
Of course, he's 19 years late.
A lot of orgasms went by, and that Ford joker's in a pen.
So I have problems with the legal system.
It doesn't work.
19 years, and I'm sorry I made a mistake.
At any rate, those media people, what they did, several of them contacted me.
I had a good reputation, still do, at least in that respect.
I've been discreet and trustworthy, and made that footage available.
us to look at for two reasons.
One, to know what the prosecution had.
And then some of it was for us to decide whether or not we wanted the prosecution to have it.
And of course, we made that decision.
And they helped.
And that's within, in fact, Lady Bird's TV station.
And that's a TV reporter.
Fuck you.
And they hated the man that was in Lady Bird.
And they hated the war.
But, you know, what can they do about it?
Well, one of them helped us a lot because some footage got destroyed that wouldn't have helped at all.
And plus, we got to see everything that the district attorney was going to be able to use.
The same way with still photographs.
A lot of people always take pictures of major demonstrations, of course.
As you'll learn if you're active, a whole lot of them are FBI.
And if the president's around, a whole lot of them are Secret Service.
But there are always a lot of cameras around.
And so then when a legal case comes out of all that, you've got hundreds of photographs that you've got to try to figure out how they're going to be used.
The media helps in that.
Now, these are individual people in the media that are helping.
So in a way, it's not the question.
The question, of course, is what is media policy?
How are they going to handle something?
That's a whole different thing.
They're going to be opposed to you.
You're going to have a very difficult time.
The TV, I rarely watch the TV news things except when there's something so burning that I have to watch it just to know if the roof's going to cave in.
Because they extract one sentence and that's supposed to be the story.
And you've got to have a lot more information than that to make any kind of decision.
A lot of that stuff in the Middle East is that way.
You just get the tip of the iceberg.
The way they carried that story about when the United States hijacked an Egyptian plane, like in Crime Against Humanity.
I mean, Reagan and the so-called big boys, they decided, screw the law, international law.
This Egyptian airline plane has got something we want.
We're going to take it and put it over here and get what we want.
Of course, the media didn't care that way.
I mean, what they cared was getting the bad boy.
The hell with international law.
And the media still hasn't talked about it in truthful terms.
And that's something that's scary.
If we're not careful, American people may get so jaded and so cynical about what's permissible and what isn't that we'll lose our sense of outrage.
And if we lose that in our sense of compassion, we're in real problems as humanity.
How did you drop out of the establishment in the mid-60s?
I mean, the establishment as in the Democratic Party, per se.
Well, by then, I think I'd learned from the civil rights movement that the basic changes were not going to come through electoral
politics through the reasoning with elected officials or just by registering people and getting out the vote.
If you know what the candidate selection process is, how a person gets to be a candidate, what's required, I've gone through that with candidates.
I've traveled all over this state for two months with that guy who ran for governor, going to all the towns and cities of any size, talking to so-called opinion-maker rich folks.
Folks, you have to line up to try to get a candidacy off the ground.

That process, along with how election campaigns are conducted, the media, the access to the media, particularly TV in the last 20 years, 30 years, the print media, how it's manipulated, what its interests are, what it will permit and not permit, if you know all that stuff, then
which I was beginning to get very acute at in the 1963 and 64 Corps.
We'd been taking licks from Jack Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson and a whole bunch of folks.
And I was beginning to know when somebody was hitting me in the head.
And I saw that, like Lyndon said, I mean, he's very honest on this one subject anyway, the squeaky wheel gets the grease.
Well, what he's saying is if you raise enough hell and put enough pressure on it,
to those things that don't basically change the system, you may get some relief, which is what happened to the Civil Rights Movement.
We got some relief.
But that was by massive pressure, and it was 1964 that I said, fuck it.
Electro-politics will never work.
We're never going to get basic change.
We're never going to have a society that feeds and clothes and works on loving relationships between people as long as we have
The property system and the legal electoral system that we've got now, we cannot change it from within.
Of course, that was an ongoing debate for years about whether you had to work from within or without.
You can get some changes from within.
The basic ones, you cannot.
The big rich are not going to share the wealth.
There ain't no way.
You've got to take it away from them.
Mal's right about that.
how you do that.

I don't want to do it with a gun, but probably at some point, if we're so fortunate as to be able to start changing property and human relationships, there will be a major confrontation between the big rich and the rest of us.
So that's why I quit.
The traditional, you know, I realized that
The basic change I was interested in, everybody having enough to eat, enough clothing, and enough liberty and freedom and loving relationships, was not going to be addressed by the American system.
And it didn't.
It still isn't.
You know, something that's real fascinating to me is this year,
Have you noticed how many of these big benefits, musical benefits, the contradiction between them and what Reagan and the establishment's putting out is just fantastic.
They put together that Aid for Africa thing.
And here's the fucking big boys who've got their wealth rolling in and out of Africa, saying, everything's a fucking door over, just leave it alone, be quiet, boys.
And of course, the musicians and all these folks get it together, a big event.
And then what happens?
Willie Nelson and the others farm aid.
Now, what Reagan and everybody's saying, farmers, that's tough.
You're just a little old bitty farmer.
I'm sorry, son, you lose.
Del Monte, that's okay.
But American agriculture is okay.
And then Willie Nelson and them, big problem.
We've got to have a big concert and benefit for the farmers.
And down in New Orleans, the jazz and blues people, they're having a big one.
for the poor people in New Orleans.
And of course Reagan said, there ain't no politics, blah, blah, blah.
And then they're doing the same thing out in California about the AIDS sign.
Because the administration doesn't want to admit that we've got a major, which that's a tragic social major problem we've got occurring, is AIDS, and that's terrifying.
If you think about it, I'm not talking about just the gay community, I'm talking about everybody.
We better lick that son of a bitch quick.
And yet we're not doing it.
applying the resources and expertise to it.
But again, there's a group of people that are getting together who have big names, big drawing power, and saying, you're lying.
There is a big problem, and we ain't doing nothing about it.
Capitalism is not geared to taking care of certain basic problems.
It's geared to benefit a relatively few people.
That's my speech for the day.
And, of course, I would like to say that the ongoing dilemma for me, as it is for a whole lot of folks, is what to do with my life.
Day to day, what do I do next?
I have a hard time with that.
We had Emma Jo's.
It was easier because there are a number of groups and organizations and activities around town, and we could plug into them.
We could have benefits for them.
We could give them a forum.
We could publicize a number of things we could do that were useful
but we don't have that place anymore.
And you have to make a living.
You have to come up with enough money to feed yourself and shelter yourself, which, by the way, is much different than the 1960s.
From about 1964 to 1968, I lived on what they called the couch circuit back in those days, which means I lived everywhere with friends in the living room or the couch on the floor.
And then I had a relationship with a dear woman, a lover for about five or six years.
And then that broke up, and again I was on the couch for a year and a half.
That's when there was heavy political activity going on.
It was a widespread sense of community.
In other words, people didn't mind as much.
We were real honest about it.
You know, you're staying too long, Mark.
You've been here a week.
getting on my nerves, or my larder's low and I can't support you, you better find some other place to go.
But we were happy to have you come back again some other time.
So there was a community of interest which doesn't exist now.
But it's very difficult, I think, now to find those things that you can work on that make a real difference.
We've got several here in Austin, there's groups working on that refugee problem out of South and Central America.
the anti-nuclear group, the Peace and Justice Coalition has been here.

We have some Chicano groups that do some good things, and some of the student groups, the PLO, not PLO, Palestinian student groups try to get a lot of information out about what's going on in the Mideast with Israel.
But what I...
What I think is that there are a whole lot of people like me who have basically the same convictions.
A lot of new people, but certainly a lot of people older that went through some of the same experiences I did.
That come the time, if Reagan tries to invade Nicaragua or the Mideast, do something totally outrageous.
Nothing.
I'm not saying a thing like Renato, which is going to stomp it or something.
What a joke that was.
But if he tries to do something outrageous, then there will be large numbers of people, a lot of Vietnam vets, that will come unglued, that will get with young people in a hurry.
And young people ain't going to want to go fighting in any banana republic about who gets the big money.
And we were talking about the military and what's the else they understood when they lost the military.
Now they've got a pretty much mercenary military.
And it's heavy black in Chicano because those are the poorest categories of groups that don't have more opportunities outside the military, so it's heavy black in Chicano inside.
Well, there's one thing that I think the big boys learned in Vietnam.
is that people of color just ain't too happy about being sent by the white man to go kill some more people of color.
So if they try to send them to Nicaragua or Salvador, they may have some of the same problems they had in Vietnam.
White officers getting their ass shot.
By black and Chicano enlisted.
Is there anything else you wanted to go into?
No, as you can tell, you've got me all excited.
I've been rattling for three or four hours.
But I've enjoyed it.
I hope it'll be helpful.
You want some of the rag people that... Rag people, and just people that were active in the 60s in Austin.
Right.
Of the rag, there's a man named Thorne Dreyer, first name T-H-O-R-N-E, last name D-R-E-Y-E-R.
Currently in Houston.
His family has a prominent art gallery there.
He's one of the founders and heavy activists in the rag.
Alice Embry, last name's spelled E-M-B-R-E-E.
in Austin, Texas, active in the RAG.
She can be reached, by the way, you'd look in the phone book on that other one.
She can be reached by contacting Alice Gwynn.
Alice Gwynn's name is spelled L-Y-C-E, last name G-U-Y-N-N.
name and number in the phone book.
She knows Alice Embry's married name, which I don't.
Her husband is an artist and works for the city.
He's Chilean.
Alice knows a whole lot about Chile.
She spent a whole lot of time in Chile.
Alice Embry would be a good person to talk to because she's active in the rag here locally.
She knows a good bit about the rap, which is a very prominent New York underground paper.
active in the women's movement, knows a whole lot about international Chilean relations and how that all developed and is still developing.
At any rate, knows quite a bit.
Dave Mahler, last name M-A-H-L-E-R, Austin phone book.
Worked on the rag for years.
Now works with what's called the Wilderness Basin in Austin, which is some acreage right on the outskirts of Austin where they're trying to preserve a certain habitat.
His friend and lover at the time active on the rag, also in the phone book, Judy Walther, W-A-L-T-H-E-R.
Marion Bizarre, last name spelled B-I-Z-A-R-D, Austin Pohnbook, works on some TV, cable TV, community cable TV committees, one of the activists and longtime people with the RAG.
The National SDS officers that came out of this area, Joe, by the way,
I can't give you a lease on all of them because I don't know, but Robert Pardun, P-A-R-D-U-N, I think he's somewhere in the Midwest, one of the smaller farming communities, but I'm not sure.
I know he lived in a commune in Arkansas for a couple of years.
A man who is here locally, who's quite articulate and very knowledgeable, who was active in the rag and who started the rat in New York City, and is now getting...
and he's very active in obtaining the new TV franchises the federal government's putting out in smaller-sized cities, is Jeff Nightbird.
Last name, N-I-G-H-T-B-Y-R-D, one word.
Former name, formal name, family name, you know, old-time name, Jeff Shero, S-C-H-E-R-O, but now is known legally as Jeff Nightbird.
Bobby Nelson, Bobby J. Nelson.
Married, but name listed in the phone book under her name.
Very active in the movement law office and with the women's movement.
active in an A&M case where they forced them to recognize gay organizations.
She had that case originally.
In fact, I went down there when the initial interviews were going on.
That was very interesting, the way they tried to shut that down.
She also brought the first sex discrimination case against the University of Texas, representing an art professor.
Very prominent case.
At any rate, Bobby Nelson, very knowledgeable, intelligent, articulate.
Okay, some of the people that I now have political differences with but really respect and have a lot of knowledge, they're apt to be more leery than some of us about talking.
Lori, L-O-R-I, Hanson, H-A-N-S-E-L.

It's a Saul Alinsky type group that I mentioned, the Acorn.
They have a lot of affiliations with church groups and businesses.
They try to get funding for small minority businesses.

Francis Barton, B-A-R-T-O-N.
Frances is, I think, finishing up her PhD.

They were organizers of various sorts, either labor organizers or Chicano organizers.
And if he's looking for a program sometime or a class, and she's a very good speaker.

Elaine Brightwater.

John Muir is very knowledgeable, very articulate.

there is an older woman a woman i guess in her late 60s now one of my dearest friends my oldest daughter is named after her her name is latane l-a-t-a-n-e lambert l-a-m-b-e-r-t active in the 30s 40s 50s 60s 70s 80s experiencing
Everything.
She started out in theater, and she and her husband were active in organizing the pecan shellers in San Antonio.
A great story.
They got married, and their wedding, they had all strikers, their own strike.
It was winter.
Big warehouse.
They all got together.
Of course, they'd been living together, sleeping lovers for a long time, but it was decided by powers that be they ought to get married.
It wasn't good PR as far as the Chicanos, who were very Catholic church oriented.
They got married.
He later, George Lambert, was an international representative of the International Ladies Vomit Workers Union.
It was a very radical, dynamic type union.
Anyway, on their wedding night, they had the strike going on, and George went out to the picket lines.

And it was colder than hell, and so the picket people, they got a barrel, which was common, and had sand in it, poured gas on it, and lit a fire to warm their hands while they were on the picket line.
And they arrested him, and she said she didn't get to fuck him for two weeks.
But Latane knows a whole lot.
In fact, part of her, I think her own papers, plus her husband, who's now dead, and there was a big article in the Observer about it when he died,
A lot of his papers are currently on file at the University of Texas at Arlington.
They relate more to Texas labor history.
Latane's been active in everything that's come down the pike.
She's currently a state employee, works for the Texas Department of Community Affairs.
I think it's more, I'll let you know, unless there's certain areas.
I could go on and on about people that I think know a whole lot.
